{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ff605eb3-a176-4d5e-afdb-52f6b46bfe57","content":"No workflow files found in this directory. Since there's no existing repo to inspect, here's a concise guide for switching to NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC):\n\n### What to change in your GitHub Actions workflow\n\n**1. Add `id-token: write` permission:**\n```yaml\npermissions:\n  id-token: write   # Required for OIDC\n  contents: read\n```\n\n**2. Replace your `dotnet nuget push` step:**\n```yaml\n# Before (API key):\n- run: dotnet nuget push **/*.nupkg -s https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json -k ${{ secrets.NUGET_API_KEY }}\n\n# After (trusted publishing):\n- run: dotnet nuget push **/*.nupkg -s https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\nNo `-k` flag needed — the OIDC token is used automatically.\n\n**3. Configure NuGet.org side:**\n- Go to **nuget.org → Manage Packages → Your Package → Trusted Publishers**\n- Add a new trusted publisher with:\n  - **Repository owner**: your GitHub org/user\n  - **Repository name**: your repo\n  - **Workflow filename**: e.g. `publish.yml`\n  - Optionally restrict to a specific **branch/tag/environment**\n\n**4. Remove the `NUGET_API_KEY` secret** from your repo settings once verified.\n\n### Key points\n- OIDC eliminates long-lived secrets — GitHub mints a short-lived token per workflow run\n- The `id-token: write` permission is the critical piece on the GitHub side\n- The NuGet.org trusted publisher config is what authorizes your repo to push\n\nWould you like me to create or modify an actual workflow file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b6b1ecb8-da22-4cfa-928c-06b95d8a7237","outputTokens":422,"requestId":"1C1F:1DC1AD:5EF83DA:6668371:69FBE2B5"},"id":"5617c622-f172-41c9-8407-4a385dd1ef01","timestamp":"2026-05-07T00:54:23.412Z","parentId":"456ebb63-0d59-4c6d-b78c-30fb455c2f02"}
